I had a friend's son staying with us for a while so he could complete the school year before moving. He and I started playing EQ right after it was released. Within a couple of weeks, his grades started dropping and he stopped hanging out with friends because he was playing too much. What did I do? Let him cut classes so he could play 12 hours a day? Sue Sony Online Entertainment? No. I cut back on his EQ time and spent time with him doing other things. Wow, taking responsibility for another's upkeep. Novel concept, I know. Maybe I should give it a name... I know! How about parenting? I wonder if it will ever catch on??? I can only hope...<br>
<br>
Edit: Afterthoughts: I do care about the people I know through playing EQ and have even met several of them in RL. Behind the protection of the keyboard, people do let their defenses down and show more of their true selves than they realize. People can also become drawn emotionally into their online lives. Once that happens, it's hard to break that bond, and could probably be considered a form of addiction. I'm sorry his mother didn't know more about her son's online life, but that wasn't his fault. It also wasn't SOE's. If they're going to put warning labels on EQ, they'd better put them on life itself also. It's possible to get emotionally caught up in it just as much or more.<br>
<br>
